{
  "card_id": "breakout_vs_manipulation",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Breakout vs Manipulation",
  "aliases": [
    "Breakout or Manipulation",
    "breakout or manipulation",
    "continuation vs reversal at relevant swing",
    "Continuation vs Reversal at Relevant Swing",
    "真突破与假突破",
    "突破与操纵"
  ],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "Two opposing reactions when price trades into a relevant swing high or low: a breakout continues beyond the level (retracement/continuation phase); a manipulation reverses back into the range (reversal phase), confirmed by candle 2 or 3 closure inside the range.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Mark only relevant swing highs/lows (extremes with valid separation from adjacent swings, within a 3-higher-time-frame-candle look-back); ignore failure swings.",
    "When price trades into the relevant swing, observe which phase of price forms: retracement/consolidation indicates a breakout (continuation), while a reversal indicates a manipulation.",
    "A manipulation is confirmed by a candle 2 or candle 3 closure back inside the range, using the wick or EQ for candle 3 to respect.",
    "If price trades into a level with no reaction and continues through, treat it as a breakout and reassign the next extreme as the new relevant swing.",
    "Reject the reaction if the swing has insufficient separation from a prior low/high (untrusted level); wait for the extreme to be taken out.",
    "Use the Fractal Model at relevant swing points to identify K-line structure for distinguishing the two behaviors."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Determines whether to fade or follow price at a key swing. A manipulation (reversal with candle 2/3 closure) sets up a trade back to the opposite side of the range or to failure swings as targets. A breakout (retracement/continuation) signals trading in the direction of the break toward the next relevant level. Misreading leads to fading genuine continuations or chasing false breakouts.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Looking for reversals at failure swings instead of relevant swings, expecting reactions where the extreme has not yet been taken.",
    "Trusting a reaction at a swing with insufficient separation from a nearby low/high.",
    "Treating a swing as permanently relevant without applying the 3-higher-time-frame-candle look-back period.",
    "Failing to update the relevant swing when price breaks through one level, making the next extreme the new relevant swing.",
    "Entering immediately upon price crossing a swing point without waiting for candle 2 or 3 closure to confirm intent."
  ],
